Article:
BNY Mellon is planning to merge two funds, citing one’s ‘better performance’.

The $111.7m BNY Mellon Structured MidCap fund is set to merge into the $5.1bn BNY Mellon Small/Mid Cap Growth fund, pending shareholder approval. According to a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), the merger would go through on or about November 5.

The larger Small/Mid Cap Growth fund has had a ‘significantly better performance record’ than its smaller sibling, the filing noted, adding: ‘Management believes that, as a result of becoming shareholders in a much larger combined fund, the reorganization should enable fund shareholders to benefit from the spreading of fixed costs across a larger asset base, which may result in a reduction of shareholder expenses.’

A BNY Mellon Investment Management spokeswoman confirmed the merger plan, acknowledged the difference in performance records, and reiterated the firm’s view that the two funds’ investment goals are ‘substantially similar.’

The larger acquiring fund offers an expense ratio of 73 basis points (bps), compared to 90bps for the smaller fund.

Peter Goslin, Syed Zamil, Adam Logan, and Chris Yao are listed on the Structured Midcap fund, while the Citywire AAA-rated manager trio of Todd Wakefield, Robert Zeuthen, and John Porter are listed on the Small/Mid Cap Growth fund.

No portfolio managers are expected to leave the firm as a result of the merger, the spokeswoman said.

iShares eyes 7 ETFs for closure

BlackRock’s iShares is preparing to liquidate a slate of seven smaller ETFs with combined assets of about $107m.

The iShares ETFs set to close, their tickers, and their most recent asset values, according to Morningstar, are as follows:

iShares Factors US Blend Style ETF (STLC) ($6m);

ETF (STLC) ($6m); iShares Factors US Mid Blend Style ETF (STMB) ($6.5m);

ETF (STMB) ($6.5m); iShares Factors US Small Blend Style ETF (STSB) ($7.3m);

ETF (STSB) ($7.3m); iShares Currency Hedged MSCI Mexico ETF (HEWW) ($722,000);

ETF (HEWW) ($722,000); iShares Adaptive Currency Hedged MSCI EAFE ETF (DEFA) ($6.7m);

ETF (DEFA) ($6.7m); iShares International Preferred Stock ETF (IPFF) ($76.2m);

ETF (IPFF) ($76.2m); iShares Russell 1000 Pure US Revenue ETF (AMCA) ($3.6m).

The firm announced the liquidations in news release and in a filing with the SEC, which noted that the funds’ boards voted unanimously in favor of liquidation but did not specify the rationales for doing so.

‘iShares regularly reviews its product lineup to meet the evolving needs of our clients,’ said a BlackRock spokesman.
